# Lab path (hands-on labs)

When the user wants the **next** **lab** generated:

## 1. Inputs and numbering

- Read **`aws_rough.txt`** at the **AWS-PROJECTS repo root** (same level as `README.md`). If the workspace root is a parent folder (e.g. monorepo), use **`AWS-PROJECTS/aws_rough.txt`**.
- If the file is empty or only whitespace, stop and ask the user to paste the rough notes or transcript first.
- Determine **`N`**: the next integer such that **`labs/N.md` does not exist**. Scan `labs/` for files named **`{number}.md`** (digits only, e.g. `1.md` … `25.md`); set **`N = max + 1`**. Ignore `all-projects.md`, `generate_labs.py`, and other non-numbered names.

## 2. Title and extraction

- Derive a clear, descriptive **Title Case** title from the rough content (e.g. “Create an S3 Static Website with CloudFront”).
- Extract all concrete steps, regions, resource names, CLI commands, console paths, and diagrams/links mentioned in the rough file. Organize into a **single coherent lab**; fill small gaps logically as an experienced AWS engineer would, without inventing major requirements the user did not imply.

## 3. Output file `labs/N.md`

Create **`labs/N.md`** with this structure (match tone and depth of existing labs like `labs/1.md`):

1. **`# Project N: {title}`**
2. Optional playlist line (keep consistent with other labs if this repo uses it):
   `> **Playlist:** [AWS Cloud LABS](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL6rbQ5F5xbtUDapCqcNV0srF8Uu-8RtSt)`
3. **`## Introduction`** — What the project is, why it matters, plain language (high-school readable).
4. **`## Technologies and tools used`** — Table: service/concept | short explanation (e.g. S3, VPC, IAM, Lambda, **Amazon Linux 2023** vs AL2, etc.).
5. **`## Step-by-step lab walkthrough`** — Detailed checklist steps (`- [ ] **...**`), grouped with `###` subheadings. Include code/console blocks where useful. Preserve any URLs or image markdown from the rough file if present.
6. **`## Conclusion`** — What was built, how to verify, security/cost/cleanup notes, and **one sentence** on when you’d use this in real life.

**Do not** add a Q&A section unless the user explicitly asks later.

## 4. Keep AWS guidance current (labs and notes)

While writing or expanding steps, **align with current AWS practice** (use official docs when unsure):

- Prefer **Amazon Linux 2023** notes where relevant: package manager **`dnf`** (not `yum` for AL2023).
- IAM: mention **least privilege**, **MFA** for privileged users; note **IAM Identity Center (SSO)** as the modern alternative to long-term access keys where appropriate.
- S3: **Block Public Access**, **Object Ownership** (ACLs often disabled), encryption defaults.
- Console names drift (e.g. **AWS WAF**); say “search in the console for …” when exact labels may vary.
- Call out **sandbox-only** patterns (`0.0.0.0/0` SSH, wide admin policies) and suggest tighter production options.

## 5. Update `README.md`

Append one line **after the last `PROJECT …` link**, same format as existing entries:

```markdown
- [ ] [PROJECT N - TITLE IN ALL CAPS](https://github.com/omeatai/AWS-PROJECTS/blob/main/labs/N.md)
```

Use the **same GitHub `blob/main` URL pattern** as the other projects. Title in the link text must be **ALL CAPS**.

## 6. After delivery

- Tell the user **`labs/N.md`** and **`README.md`** were updated.
- Remind them they can **clear or replace `aws_rough.txt`** when starting the next project so the next run does not mix content.
